Finish the system-variables inventory (Phase 1.5).

Phase 1 of issues/open/system-variables.issue landed in commit
b071d73 ("spec/documentation: add system-variables-inventory.sexp") as
`autolisp-spec/documentation/system-variables-inventory.sexp`: 1417
records (676 :both, 739 :bricscad, 2 :autocad). It is machine-readable
(`READ` returns 1417 forms in SBCL with no error), schema-conformant,
and every record carries `:versions` and `:source` provenance.

What is NOT yet covered — and what this follow-up addresses — is the
AutoCAD-side enumeration, the divergence transcription, the literal
default-value verification, and the :coupled expansion. Phase 2 (spec
chapter) and Phase 3 (clautolisp implementation) of the parent issue
remain blocked on a *complete* and *vendor-symmetric* inventory.

Convention: this issue tracks the residual Phase-1 work. When each
task lands, move its entry to the Resolved tail at the bottom of this
file.

== Open work items ==

=== I. AutoCAD-side enumeration ===

The Bricsys sitemap gave us 1415 names in one shot. The Autodesk help
SPA (help.autodesk.com/view/ACD/2026/ENU/) has no analogous public
sitemap or A-Z index URL. Per-page HTM endpoints
(`/cloudhelp/2026/ENU/AutoCAD-Core/files/GUID-XXX.htm`) DO return
pre-rendered content with the expected metadata
(`<meta name="topic-subtype" content="sysvar"/>`,
`<meta name="contextid" content="NAME"/>`, plus the
`Type:` / `Saved in:` / `Initial value:` table) — but the GUID set is
not discoverable through any plain HTTP endpoint I could find.

Required:

  - Walk the AutoCAD 2026 ENU Commands and System Variables Reference
    table-of-contents via the Chrome MCP. Recurse into the
    "System Variables" sub-tree and harvest every `(NAME, GUID)`
    pair. The TOC is built at runtime from JS data (the SPA's
    `Boot.Config.tocPath`); a real Chromium walk — the same approach
    `vendor-inventory-2026.org` already used to dump BricsCAD's
    `chmtop.c2wtopf.TITEMS` tree — is the path of least resistance.
  - Persist the harvested mapping to `/tmp/sv-build/acad-toc.txt`
    (one `NAME<TAB>GUID` per line, sorted), then fetch every
    per-sysvar page in bulk via `xargs -P 25 curl` (the existing
    BricsCAD scrape script in `git log` is a working template — see
    the Phase-1 commit).
  - Parse each page with the same field-extraction skeleton used for
    Bricsys (Python regex). Map vendor types:
        Real    -> :real
        Short   -> :short
        Long    -> :integer
        String  -> :string
        Bitcode -> :integer  (set :bitcoded t, list bits in :summary)
        3D-point/2D-point -> :point3d / :point
    Map "Saved in" verbatim ('Drawing', 'Registry', 'Not-saved', etc.)
    onto the existing scope/saved-in keywords (`:drawing`, `:registry`,
    `:session`, `:preference`).
  - Also fetch the Updated / New / Obsolete reference pages
    (GUID-4FEBA606-…, GUID-B93A458E-…, GUID-5647ACE3-…) and use them
    to set the `:versions :autocad` field correctly per name.
  - Union the new AutoCAD records into the existing inventory:
      * If a name already exists in the inventory: merge — fill
        `:divergence` with the AutoCAD/BricsCAD delta (default,
        range, scope, read-only, type), upgrade `:vendor` to `:both`
        if it was `:autocad` or `:bricscad`, and add the AutoCAD URL
        to `:source` (`:autocad "https://help.autodesk.com/..."`).
      * If the name is new: append as `:vendor :autocad` with the
        usual fields.
  - Expected outcome: total count rises from 1417 toward ~1900-2100,
    `:autocad` vendor count rises from 2 to ~hundreds, and `:both`
    is the dominant bucket.

Done when the inventory's `:autocad` and `:bricscad` and `:both`
counts each reflect the actual vendor namespaces with documented
provenance for every record.

=== II. Divergence transcription for shared sysvars ===

For the 676 `:vendor :both` records, `:divergence` is currently NIL.
The Bricsys page and the matching AutoCAD page often agree on the
sysvar's name and intent but differ on default, range, scope,
read-only-ness, or even type. The inventory should record those
deltas as short prose.

Required:

  - After step I, for every `:vendor :both` record, diff the
    AutoCAD-side and BricsCAD-side captured tuples
    (type, default, read-only, range, saved-in). When any field
    differs, fill `:divergence` with a single sentence such as
        "AutoCAD default 4133, BricsCAD default 4135."
        "AutoCAD :saved-in :drawing, BricsCAD :saved-in :registry."
    Keep both vendors' specifics elsewhere in the record (preserve
    the existing field as the *Bricsys* value; an explicit
    `:default-acad` / `:type-acad` extension may be added if needed).
  - When the two pages agree (modulo trivial whitespace), leave
    `:divergence NIL`.

Done when no `:vendor :both` record's underlying-vendor table-rows
differ without `:divergence` describing the difference.

=== III. Literal defaults for the 223 `:default (:unknown)` records ===

Bricsys-derived records where the page row reads "Varies" /
"Depends on …" / is blank were set to `:default (:unknown)`. Many
of these are genuinely host-/drawing-/session-specific (correctly
marked); some, however, *do* have a documented constant on the
AutoCAD side (or in the parent UNITS/SETVAR prose on the Bricsys
side) that the parser missed because the row used an unusual layout
or was on a sibling "Possible options" table.

Required:

  - Grep the inventory for `:default (:unknown)`. For each, check
    the AutoCAD page captured in step I and the Bricsys page already
    cited in `:source` — re-read the prose, not just the table — and
    either:
      * upgrade to a literal default (e.g. `0`, `"0"`, `0.0`,
        `"BYLAYER"`), or
      * replace `(:unknown)` with the more specific marker
        `(:host-specific)` / `(:drawing)` / `(:session)` /
        `(:registry)` per the documentation. `(:unknown)` should
        only survive when the vendor *actually says* nothing.
  - The 223 candidates as of commit b071d73 start with:
      ACADPREFIX ACADVER AREA AUDITERRORCOUNT BASEFILE
      BCFSOURCEURL BIMPROFILESTANDARDS BLOCKEDITOR BLOCKSPATH
      BMFORMTEMPLATEPATH CDATE CENTEREXE CHECKDWLPRESENCE
      CIRCULARARROW… CMDNAMES CMLSCALE COLORBOOKPATH
      COMMANDASSIST COMMUNICATORPATH COMPONENTSCONFIG
      COMPONENTSPATH CPLOTSTYLE CTRLMBUTTON CURSORMODE
      CVERSIONCONTROLPATH DATACOLLECTION* DATE DBLCLKEDIT DBMOD
      DCTCUST DCTMAIN DEFAULT* DETAILSPATH DGNIMPSYMBOLRESOURCEFILES
      DIASTAT DIM* (many)…
    `(grep -E ":default \(:unknown\)" ../system-variables-inventory.sexp -B1 | grep :name | sort)`
    will list the full set.

Done when `(:unknown)` survives only on sysvars where the vendor
docs themselves omit a documented value, and all "host-specific"
markers are explicit.

=== IV. Per-record `:coupled` AutoLISP-function list ===

Most records ship with `:coupled ()`. The seed table from Phase 1
covers the well-known couplings (angle / units / file / error /
security / user-scratch families plus the issue's listed pairs).
Phase 3 of the parent issue (clautolisp implementation) needs the
full list because each coupling becomes a concrete `setvar` /
`getvar` call inside the affected builtin.

Required:

  - For each sysvar, grep both vendor pages and the AutoLISP /
    BricsCAD-LISP references for AutoLISP/Visual-LISP function names
    that *read* or *write* the sysvar. Concretely:
      * help.autodesk.com AutoLISP Reference — most sysvars are
        cross-linked from the relevant function entries (e.g.
        `osnap` from OSMODE, `acad_strlsort` from MAXSORT).
      * BricsCAD's "Related Information / Lisp" sidebars on each
        sysvar page already list a "Lisp" cross-reference where
        applicable.
      * The inventory schema's existing :coupled seed table in the
        Phase-1 build script is the starting point — extend rather
        than replace.
  - Standardise on lowercase function names (the schema uses
    `"angtos"` not `"ANGTOS"`).
  - When confident the sysvar has no AutoLISP coupling beyond the
    raw `getvar`/`setvar` round trip (e.g., the USERI*/USERR*/USERS*
    scratch slots, drawing-metadata reads like DBMOD), leave `()`.

Done when `:coupled` lists every AutoLISP function the spec or
either vendor's docs cites as reading or writing the sysvar.

=== V. False-positive audit on the "BricsCAD only" prose detector ===

The Phase-1 parser flagged `:vendor :bricscad` whenever the page
prose contains the literal string "BricsCAD only", filtered through
a tiny `FALSE_BRICSCAD_ONLY` whitelist (in the build script). The
detector is conservative but not infallible — a page can mention
"…in BricsCAD only when ZWS is enabled…" and trigger a false flag.

Required:

  - For every `:vendor :bricscad` record, spot-check by name against
    the AutoCAD 2026 SPA (step I gives the full AutoCAD inventory;
    a join on name is sufficient). Promote to `:vendor :both` and
    set `:source :autocad` whenever AutoCAD also documents the
    sysvar.
  - Update the build script's `FALSE_BRICSCAD_ONLY` set as new
    cases come to light, so a re-run of the parser stays correct.

Done when the `:vendor :bricscad` bucket reflects sysvars that are
*genuinely* absent from AutoCAD's 2026 reference, not just sysvars
whose Bricsys page happens to mention "BricsCAD only" in passing.

== Reproducibility notes ==

The Phase-1 commit (b071d73) shows the parser pattern: download all
pages (1415 of them) under /tmp/bx-pages, parse with
`/tmp/sv-build/parse_bricsys.py`, build the .sexp with
`/tmp/sv-build/build_sexp.py`. Re-run sequence after AutoCAD-side
work:

   1. Run a Chrome-MCP TOC walk to produce /tmp/sv-build/acad-toc.txt
      (one NAME<TAB>GUID per line).
   2. xargs -P 25 curl every GUID page into /tmp/acad-pages/.
   3. Adapt parse_bricsys.py → parse_acad.py for the AutoCAD HTM
      structure (`<meta name="contextid">` for the name,
      `<meta name="topic-subtype" content="sysvar">` to filter,
      the `Type:` / `Saved in:` / `Initial value:` rows, the
      `(Read-only)` marker).
   4. Re-run build_sexp.py with both `bricsys.json` and `acad.json`
      sources; let it union by name, diff to fill `:divergence`,
      and emit the merged inventory.
   5. SBCL `READ`-validate as before. Bump the inventory header
      comment and commit.

== Acceptance criteria ==

  - [ ] AutoCAD-side enumeration step (I) merged: `:autocad` vendor
        bucket non-trivial, every record has both `:source :autocad`
        and `:source :bricscad` where the sysvar is shared.
  - [ ] Divergence step (II) merged: no `:vendor :both` record's
        underlying vendor table-rows disagree silently.
  - [ ] Default-verification step (III) merged: `:default (:unknown)`
        only survives where the docs themselves omit a value.
  - [ ] Coupling expansion step (IV) merged: `:coupled` reflects the
        cross-references published in each vendor's reference.
  - [ ] False-positive audit step (V) merged: `:vendor :bricscad`
        bucket reflects AutoCAD-absence, not just prose mentions.
  - [ ] `sbcl --non-interactive --eval '(with-open-file (s "system-variables-inventory.sexp") (loop for f = (read s nil :eof) until (eq f :eof) count t))'`
        still returns a clean integer count with no reader errors.
  - [ ] Phase 2 (spec chapter) and Phase 3 (clautolisp
        implementation) of the parent issue
        `issues/open/system-variables.issue` are unblocked.

